Product Version     25.10    Cadence Design Systems, Inc.
assignTSV(25.10)                                              assignTSV(25.10)

Name
       assignTSV  -  Assigns nets to TSVs and/or frontside and backside bumps,
       and/or feedthrus

Syntax
       assignTSV

       [-help]

       [-write_down_level_bump]

       [-selected <netName> | [[-signal | -pgpad ] [-feedthru | -nonFeedthru ]
       [-net <netlist> | -exclude_net <excludeNetList>] [-area  <llx  lly  urx
       ury ...>] [-exclude_region <llx lly urx ury ...>] [-tsvViaName <tsvVia-
       CellName>] [-interposer ] ] ]

       [{[-backBump ] [-frontBump ]} [-force_current_die ]]

       Assigns  nets  to  TSVs  and/or  frontside  and  backside bumps, and/or
       feedthrus. The command considers all dies in the 3D IC System by  using
       the  die  abstract  files, and optimizes bump assignment for the global
       nets which connect these dies. If you run the  readDieAbstract  command
       to import die abstract files of other chips inside the 3D IC System be-
       fore  running  the  assignTSV command, assignTSV will optimize TSV/bump
       assignment by considering the whole system.

       Note: Use this command after the TSVs and bumps are created and the in-
       stances connected with the IO pins are placed.

Parameters
       -help  Print out the command usage.

       -backBump
              Declares that the back side bumps and the TSVs will be  assigned
              automatically.

       -force_current_die
              Assigns all IO pins to backside bumps or frontside bump directly
              without checking the XML file and the top level netlist.

              You  can  use -force_current_die only if -backBump or -frontBump
              is specified.

       -frontBump
              Declares that the front side bumps will be assigned with the  IO
              pins automatically.

       -tsvViaName <tsvViaCellName>
              If  this  option  is  specified,  only the TSV with the VIA cell
              tsvViaCellName will be assigned. Others will be ignored.

       -selected <netName>
              Assigns the selected TSVs and bumps with a specified net.

              Note: If the selected TSV  belongs  to  a  feedthru,  the  whole
              feedthru will be assigned with the net.

              This  option  is  used for manual assignment and is exclusive to
              any other options for auto assignment.

       -signal
              Declares that only signal will be assigned.

       -pgpad Declares that only power/ground net will be assigned.

       -feedthru
              Declares that the command assigns only the feedthru net.

       -nonFeedthru
              Declares that the command assigns only the nonfeedthru signal or
              power/ground net.

       -net <netlist>
              Assigns the specified nets to the near TSV/bumps.

       -exclude_net <excludenetlist>
              Excludes the nets in the specified boxes.

       -area {<llx lly urx ury> ...}
              Assigns the TSV/bump within the box only.

       -exclude_region {<llx lly urx ury> ...}
              Excludes the TSV/bumps in the specified boxes.

       -interposer
              Declares that the assignment is done in silicon interposer with-
              out any instance.

       -write_down_level_bump
              Writes down the level bump file for each hierarchical instance.

       Notes:

              * If neither -signal nor -pgpad is specified,  both  signal  and
                pgpad will be assigned.

              * If  neither  -feedthru  nor  -nonFeedthru  is  specified, both
                feedthru and non-feedthru net will be assigned.

              * If neither -frontBump nor -backBump is selected, none  of  the
                bumps  will  be  assigned.  However, the TSV will still be as-
                signed.

Examples
              * The following command  assigns  the  signal  IO  pins  to  the
                frontside bump:

                assignTSV -frontBump -signal

              * The following command assigns the selected TSV with net VDD:

                addTSV -selected VDD

Related Information
